******
[3] National
Date: Thu 22 Mar 2012
Source: EMOL [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
http://www.emol.com/noticias/nacional/2012/03/22/532183/isp-confirma-dos-nuevos-casos-de-virus-hanta-en-el-pais.html

The Institute of Public Health (ISP) confirmed today, Thu [22 Mar 2012], 2 new hantavirus [infection] cases, in the 8th Region and in the Metropolitan Region, bringing to 30 the number of people infected with this disease [virus] in the country so far in 2012.

Of the 30 cases of hantavirus cardiopulmonary syndrome confirmed by the ISPm the Universidad Austral and the Laboratorio de la Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Chile, 8 have died, of which 5 have been registered in the BioBio region. The other deaths from [a] hantavirus [infection] have occurred in the Maule, La Araucania and Metropolitan regions, with one case in each.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[4] Metropolitan and BioBio regions
Date: Mon 19 Mar 2012
Source: Radio UChile [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
http://radio.uchile.cl/noticias/144420/

The Institute of Public Health this Sunday [18 Mar 2012] confirmed the appearance of 2 new cases of [a] hantavirus [infection] in the Metropolitan and BioBio regions. The cases are 2 young men ages 21 and 20 years. The 1st is being attended to in the Clinica Alemana and the 2nd in the Sanatorio Aleman of Concepcion.

With these, the number of confirmed cases has increased 61 per cent over those in 2011.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>




[The hantavirus involved in all of these cases has not been specified, but is most likely to be Andes virus. The long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_) is the reservoir host of Andes virus, and people are exposed to the virus through contact with excrement and urine of these infected rodents. Chilean health professionals have reduced the case fatality rate to approximately 35 per cent, a significant improvement but still high due to the rapid progression of pulmonary and cardiac distress.

An image of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at
http://www.bios.niu.edu/frayjorge/rod6.jpg

A map of Chile showing the regions mentioned can be accessed at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/txu-oclc-310606106-chile_adm09.jpg and HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Chile at http://healthmap.org/r/21Ss. - Mod. TY]
